metadata.name: strokes-1 #9
metadata.description:
A generative abstract painting using layers of strokes of different size, strength and color.

The painting is rendered by simulating one stroke at a time. The recipe is similar for all paintings. First, wide faint brush strokes cover the canvas with a background texture, then a few strong brush strokes give the piece some character. After that, very fine rapid strokes give the piece some interesting detail and finally, dabs of very short brush strokes are applied for additional sense of depth. 

The rendering takes some time. With large screen sizes, you get bigger pictures (for printing!), but the rendering is slower. 

Once the work is painted, you can hit 's' to save a png file. 

There are 7 different colour schemes.

metadata.name: Planetary Abstracts #127
metadata.description:
A hazy planet looms large in an alien solar system. The image is "drawn" over 1,000 iterations with colored pencils on textured paper. The final image takes about 40-50 seconds.

The image size is 1200x1200. Press 's' to save a screenshot or 'p' to pause and resume drawing.

Common features:
- 50 color palettes
- Planet size, full view to partial
- 3 to 8 moons
- 2 noise methods
- 4 color modes
- 3 focus areas (line thickness)
- Vertical or horizontal accent bars

Uncommon
- Monochrome color palette
- Mono with color highlights
- Mono with gold highlights

Rare
- Mono with dark background

metadata.name: My essence, My Connectible #85
metadata.description:

My Connectible is My Essence, it is as alive as I am, it is always in motion.

Features:

‚ö° 17 color skins /themes/: –°olor Sketch, X-Ray, Black Marble, –°oral, Pure Color, Marine, Vintage, Scheme, Chalks, Reverse, Jazz, Copper, Ball Pen, Grunge, Neon, Dusted Truffle, Violet. Each theme contains 1-7 palettes.

‚ö° Two background textures: either dots or lines.

‚ö° Three types of entities: —Åircles, triangles, and rhombuses. They have a core... or they don't.

Animation saving works in test mode (Chrome only): press 'open live' button, press 'S', wait 10-15 seconds. The saved GIF will open in a pop-up window or a new tab.

metadata.name: Slanted #80
metadata.description:
Fun little game, simple rules:
- start with a randomly sized grid
- pick 2 random cells
- recursively, every cell draw itself
- then it picks two of its neighbors for the next step

Some cells are drawn multiple times, some others are never picked up, but the process it's not completely random.

metadata.name: Organicon, variation I #446
metadata.description:
Generative art by Frederik Vanhoutte, @wblut
A unique generator creating an endless sequence of iterations with fixed features

Organicon, variation I is a slow piece, meant to build on the screen. Warning: the preview thumbnail is a pale shadow of live view.

Interface: a first mouse click clears the screen, creates an new iteration and enables active mode. In active mode each iteration remains on screen for a limited amount of time before being replaced by the next. A second mouse click disables active mode. In active mode a small dot is displayed in the lower right corner. '+' and '-' zoom in and out.

metadata.name: Penumbra #121
metadata.description:
Penumbra is a geometric exploration of the possible outcomes from 3 basic rules:

1) Place some walls
2) Place some light sources
3) Draw the resulting shadows

This series is a small thank you to the collectors of Umbra :)

metadata.name: Impending Cloths #108
metadata.description:
IC makes use of fabric's potential for contrasts.
The same piece of cloth can seem to be falling, perfectly still and ready to be blown away, all at the same time.
It can look "very digital" while also achieving a high degree of texture. And so on, and so forth. Contrast and potential.
Also, "h" can be pressed to download in high resolution, although it may take up to a minute.

metadata.name: Jantar Mantar #30
metadata.description:
Inspired by Jantar Mantar, an architectural site in New Delhi / India, composed of several astronomy instruments.
Jantar Mantar literally means "instruments for measuring the harmony of the heavens".
An inspiring place where geometric shapes and shadows are strictly organized around the purpose of science.

Created in javascript / webGL using three.js and pathtracer.
June 2022
@arthurmchr

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
Path tracing is an heavy GPU operation.
Depending on the device, it can takes a few seconds to render.
Worked on Chrome and Firefox.

In live mode :
press S to export a PNG of the rendered image.
press P to pause / resume rendering (automatically paused after 100 rendering steps).

metadata.name: Elemental walks II #53
metadata.description:
"Elemental walks II" is an extended exploration of the interaction and perception of different systems. The generated double grid pattern, the first system, transforms into a crowd of random walkers, this second system moves in random but constrained ways, and with each movement a third system is generated: the texture.

Use the 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 keys to switch between 5 states of movement within the dynamic pattern, you can pause ('p'), speed up ('+') or slow down ('-') the movement. 

Click on the canvas and the colours change within the composition.

'r' to reset position or release the walkers
'p' to toggle pause/play

'1' for vertical movement
'2' for diagonal movement
'3' for horizontal movement
'4' for a second diagonal movement
'5' for vertical and horizontal movement

'-' to slow down
'+' for faster movement

's' save png
'j' save jpg

metadata.name: ____ - Iteration 2 #352
metadata.description:
This project is part of a larger experiment that explores and celebrates the process of making generative art by progressively releasing iterations, working towards a final release on my main account (tz1RkYY3jr1ocuPdQqrRefr5FqoawKQsmBmD). The iterations will be titled ____ - Iteration 1, ____ - Iteration 2, etc. At this point, the number of iterations has not been determined, but more information will be provided as this experiment unfolds.

The final release will only be made available to those who have collected each iteration (using an allowlist), and will be released for free.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.
